occurrenceRemarks: We saw at least three seedlings in this canyon with opposite linear leaves, and maybe one or two more. Each of those three is posted in a separate obs. The stem color of some parts of these babies is very different from the stem color of mature A. albicans plants, but it is the same as new growth on at least two mature A. albicans plants that I and Don Rideout have photographed, including one from Don Rideout from this canyon on this trip: https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/145301755 The base of the leaves, and the way they are attached from the stem, are identical in these plants to those in new growth on A. albicans plants. The next obs: https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/145309139 has the best pix of the stem hairs. Those hairs are sparse and curved, fitting exactly the stem hairs of new growth on Asclepias albicans. This area only has A. albicans; A. subulata is only found miles away in Vallecito Wash. The baby plant in the third post is at the feet of the first mature A. albicans plants seen on this trip. We saw a similar plant four years ago that we speculated at the time was Euphorbia eriantha. But that determination seems unlikely here, since there were also a handful of Euphorbia eriantha plants in the canyon on this trip, shown in these posts: https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/145286944 https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/145227835 https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/145304206 Those plants all had alternate leaves, and were flowering or fruiting. The similar plant from four years ago: https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/145368039 All the Asclepias posts from this trip: This observation of a baby plant: https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/145309138 Second and third baby plants: https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/145309139 https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/145309140 Mature plants growing with the third baby plant: https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/145309141 https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/145309142
name: Asclepias albicans S.Watson

occurrenceRemarks: Steep mountains composed of Pre-Cenozoic granitic and metamorphic rocks, with sparse desert shrubs. Steep ridges and slopes, with canyon bottoms had a medley size of rocks and boulders. Canyon bottom had areas with heavy sand too. The canyon drains northwest, then turns sharply south parallel with the road. Canyon is incised into the bajada, with a loose, sandy slope at this area, and a wider wash of a bottom. Associated shrubs include: Larrea tridentata, Ambrosia dumosa, Krameria erecta, Hyptis emoryi, Eriogonum fascicualtum flavoviride, Encelia farinosa, Pleurocoronis pluriseta, Peucephyllum schottii, Crossosoma bigelovii, Yucca schidigera, Nolina bigelovii, Acacia greggii, (with Phoradendron californicum on it, within canyon bottoms), Xylorhiza tortifolia, Hymenoclea salsola, Trixis californica, Adenophyllum porophylloides, Bebbia juncea aspera, and Viguiera parishii. Many annuals too, with some already pass flowering. Growing within sandy canyon bottom. 9-10 feet tall.
name: Asclepias albicans S.Watson
locality: BLMNorthwest end of the Sheep Hole Mountains; Along east side of Amboy Road, around Sheep Hole Pass. Parked at a tramission tower just off the road.Near 34.239282N, 115.720544W. General collecting along bajada to west side of mountains, up ridge to 34.23506N, 115.70664W. Then down south side of this ridge to dry canyon bottom at 34.23458N, 115.70953W. Then follow this canyon bottom back out of the mountains.
